<p>Store bottles at <strong>55-58°F with 60-70% humidity</strong>, positioned horizontally to keep corks moist. Pinot Noir's delicate structure makes it particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations and light exposure. A consistent, cool environment preserves the wine's elegant aromatics and prevents premature oxidation.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Indicators</h3>
<p>Properly aged Pinot Noir develops <strong>brick-red color</strong> and complex earthy aromas while maintaining bright acidity. Warning signs include browning beyond brick tones, vinegar-like smells, or cork taint (musty, wet cardboard odors). Most sub-$20 Pinot Noirs show their best within 3-5 years, offering optimal fruit-to-earth balance before declining.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
