  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant Pinot Noir under $20 or serve it straight from the bottle?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Pinot Noir under $20 doesn't require decanting since these wines are made for immediate consumption and won't have significant sediment or overly tight tannins. However, opening the bottle 30-60 minutes before serving allows the wine to breathe and can help integrate flavors, especially for slightly more structured examples from producers like La Crema or Bogle. The delicate nature of Pinot Noir means extended decanting (over 2 hours) can actually diminish its aromatic complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Pinot Noir under $20 good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, affordable Pinot Noir is excellent for beginners because it's typically lighter in tannins and alcohol than Cabernet Sauvignon or Malbec, making it more approachable. The bright acidity and fruit-forward profile of wines like Firesteed or Mark West help newcomers identify classic red wine flavors without overwhelming bitterness. These wines also pair well with a wide range of foods, from grilled chicken to salmon, giving beginners versatile pairing experience.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying cheap Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing mass-produced wines from hot climates like Central Valley California, which often lack the delicate character that makes Pinot Noir special. Many buyers also grab the cheapest option without checking the vintage—Pinot Noir is best consumed within 2-3 years of release for wines under $20. Another error is expecting the same complexity as $50+ bottles; instead, focus on clean fruit expression and food-friendly acidity rather than seeking intense earth or spice notes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I store opened Pinot Noir under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Opened Pinot Noir under $20 typically stays fresh for 3-4 days when re-corked and refrigerated, slightly longer than heavier reds due to its naturally high acidity. Use a wine preserver or vacuum pump to extend this to 5-6 days maximum. These wines don't improve with extended exposure to air like premium Pinots, so it's best to enjoy them within a few days of opening for optimal fruit expression and freshness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What food pairings work best with budget Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Budget Pinot Noir's bright acidity and moderate tannins make it perfect for salmon, roasted chicken, pork tenderloin, and mushroom-based dishes. The wine's typically fruit-forward profile complements tomato-based pasta sauces and pizza better than more expensive, earth-driven Pinots. Avoid pairing with very spicy foods or heavy beef dishes, as the wine's delicate structure can be overwhelmed—save those pairings for more robust reds under $20 like Côtes du Rhône or Tempranillo.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good alternatives to Pinot Noir under $20 with similar characteristics?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Beaujolais-Villages offers similar light body and bright fruit character, often with better value due to less demand than Pinot Noir. Loire Valley reds like Chinon or Bourgueil provide comparable earthiness and food-friendliness, while Dolcetto from Piedmont shares Pinot's approachable tannins and cherry flavors. For domestic options, cool-climate Grenache from Santa Barbara or Barbera from Paso Robles can deliver similar versatility and freshness at competitive prices.</p>
